    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e6b5688f8f833c16",
      "text": "The main topic of this paper is system time in social systems. In today's theories of social systems, references to time are made quite frequently, as is evident, for example, in the \"thorough temporalization of elementary concepts\" (Luhmann 1984:28=1993/95:16). (1) However, it is not clear why this reference to time is so often necessary. It is generally accepted that social system theory is heavily influenced by phenomenology. In the same way that phenomenology regarded the problem domain of time as the most fundamental,(2) the problem of time may also fundamentally support the entire system theory. For the record, such speculations are not merely groundless to open a debate, nor are they intended to justify the system theory by borrowing the authority of an establi-cation called phenomenology, which has a wide following. In fact, today's social system theory has a more fundamental internal relationship to phenomenology than merely an influence relationship. For some reason, the following points are often overlooked. In other words, communication, which is an element of the social system, can only be about something at all times. This corresponds to the structure of directionality that makes phenomenology possible. In other words, something communicated is always an internal manifestation of the social system, or in other words, a social phenomenon, as opposed to an awareness phenomenon. The reason why social systems theory must address the issue of system time is that this social phenomenon is related to the current state of the system at any given time."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cf6497072f1b647c",
      "text": "The fact that a social phenomenon appears as it does now, and changes as it does, is synonymous with the constant changes of system time. However, it is not easy, but rather rather difficult, to discuss time in social systems, given the current level of sociological theory. First of all, the existence of the social system itself may be questioned to a greater or lesser degree. In this respect, in the genealogy of the philosophy of consciousness, the certainty of the thinking self was the starting point, so it was not so difficult to discuss the time of consciousness as a consequence of the development from this point. In contrast, however, in the case of social systems, the very existence of the system itself is in doubt for theories of action that do not recognize irreducible emergent properties and for a kind of utilitarianism that regards the system concept as a mere model for analysis, and unless this part is confirmed, there is little room to discuss systemic time. Therefore, we cannot discuss system time unless we are sure of this part."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0ed17c36f7086c69",
      "text": "Therefore, before a naive discussion of social system time as a subject can be made, its thematic potential must first be questioned. As an aside, without any further argument, let me suggest that the question of the existence of a social system is almost synonymous with the question of system time. In other words, it would not be right to say that the social system exists first as a kind of pure ego, and then we can finally discuss system time in analogy with the experiential flow. If we assume the order to be all the way through, it seems more plausible that the opposite is true, i.e., that we can discuss system time and then thematize the reality of the system. This is because the autonomy of a system can be described as \"temporal autonomy\" (Bergmann 1981:110). A system processes external events according to its internal temporal order, and therefore must always understand its boundary as a \"temporal boundary\" (Bergmann 1981:109). System-specific time is what guarantees (or even enforces) the system's differentiation from its environment and its autonomy (3)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "20b80d25a4ac4266",
      "text": "Therefore, in other words, a system without inherent time cannot reproduce itself autonomously and cannot be realistic. This paper, however, does not address this issue head-on. It would require more space. Therefore, keeping these issues in mind, we will only ask how the \"as it is now (Jetzt und So)\" aspect of system time can exist in the first place as an issue for the time being(4). As is well known, the challenge of modern social system theory is to observe how and why the system is being observed. This differs from a theory that attempts an objectivistic mercantilist viewpoint, such as that of a patient with a theoretical disease, in that it sets the problem in the first place. The difference between the two may be characterized as a shift from existence theory to recognition theory in system theory. Social system theory views various social systems not as mono, which is an internal relationship between the whole and its parts, but as one of the world's subjects with its own external environment.5 As an illustration of this, the theory of social systems is a theory that considers the social system as an entity with its own external environment, and as such, it is a theory of social systems. (5) As an illustration, social system theory is a second-order observer that observes the observer called the social system. And this is precisely the reason for setting the subject of this paper as mentioned above. In other words, the \"as-is\" aspect of system time is the starting point for observation of the system as it exists at any given time, and is always a blind spot or, in the manner of phenomenology, always anonymous to the system itself. Therefore, the observation of how such and such an aspect could be as it is now is considered to be a central issue for the social system theory of the second-order observer."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fa4dfe961d6fbcbf",
      "text": "In this respect, the question of system time is not limited to mere time theory, but concerns the very basis of system theory itself."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a4da17067460d85e",
      "text": "In this paper, I will call social system theory \"sociological phenomenology\" based on the correlation between social systems and social phenomena, which is based on the structure of communicative orientation. Although the attempts at a phenomenological sociology represented by Alfred Schutz have made a great contribution to sociology from a epistemological perspective, the chosen grounding system has always been consciousness-oriented, and in that sense it is only sociology made into phenomenology. Therefore, later developments of phenomenological sociology continue to strive to sociologize phenomenological sociology through concepts such as reciprocal action, language, and the living world. However, the connection between phenomenology and pragmatic theory is not as inevitable as one might think. This is because it was the orientation structure of consciousness, rather than the subject itself, that made phenomenology possible. Therefore, if we realize that the structure of related orientations can also be found between social systems and social phenomena, we can finally sociologize phenomenology. Again, as with consciousness, communication is always about something. This is sociological phenomenology. This proposal, however, is not merely a shift of the theoretical basis from the subject of consciousness to the social system. It would also entail a fundamental shift in the original point of departure of phenomenological sociology."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "695dda057c465569",
      "text": "According to phenomenological sociology, the problem of meaning is a problem of time. Schutz wrote in his major work: \"By a rough analysis, the problem of meaning is the problem of time. Schutz stated in his main work: \"A rough analysis has already shown that the problem of meaning is a problem of time. This question of time is not a question of physical space-time, which can be divided or measured, nor is it a question of historical time, which is limited to a passage filled with external events, but it is a question of \"internal time consciousness,\" of each individual's unique sense of continuity. For the experiencer, the meaning of his or her various experiences is constituted thereby\" (Schutz 1932:9-10=1982:24). This problematization was possible because phenomenological sociology could assume that the subject's internal time is always present prior to meaning, and thus unquestionable. The distinction between subjective and objective time is not as clear as it could be. The specificity of subjective time, which should be separated from objective time, is left unexplored, except for the use of such terms as continuity and experience. In fact, the image of inner time that emerges from this consideration is not so different from that of linearized, spatialized objective time. This is because rational action, one of the main themes of phenomenological sociology, can only be scaled in terms of spatialized and objective time, and there is no way to set up the purpose and means of rational action(6)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "803a4f632d512851",
      "text": "According to phenomenological sociology, social science contains issues that have different meanings from those of the natural sciences. To thematize these issues, it was thought necessary to support the analysis of internal temporal consciousness of phenomenology. In reality, however, phenomenological sociology seems to have overturned rather than assisted the phenomenological view, as later summarized by the term \"epoché of natural attitudes. Originally, in Husserl's phenomenology, a natural attitude was an attitude that made naturalized and spatialized notions of time self-evident, and this attitude had to be returned in order to approach an inner sense of time.7 However, in contrast to this, Husserl's phenomenology is not a natural attitude, but an attitude that is not naturalized, but an attitude that is not naturalized, but an attitude that is not naturalized, but an attitude that is not naturalized, and this attitude has to be returned in order to approach an inner sense of time. In contrast, phenomenological sociology considered that the natural attitude is an immersion in continuity, and that this naivete must be returned for rational action, and that an intermediate goal must be established in a reflective way. This view may lead to the following conclusion. The meaning of an act, in other words, is distinguished by the spatialization of subjective time. Internal time must be spatialized as divisible through reflection. Only then can the meaning of experience be made salient, and the meaning of action, i.e., the rational relation between purpose and means, be made possible. Therefore, according to phenomenological sociology, the unit of action is a function of the \"span\" of the projection (Schutz 1932:62=1982:83)(8)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a3f7708b8fd9ddbd",
      "text": "In the end, however, it seems that phenomenological sociology has seldom clarified the subjective reason for the subjective time that is distinct from the objective time. This was not surprising, since time was considered more fundamental than meaning in the question's formulation. At any rate, phenomenological sociology avoided from the outset the complexities of internal time, as Husserl did. One must be careful not to naively celebrate such avoidance as a wise move within the realm of empirical science. Instead, phenomenological sociology had to consider the following factors If the subject matter of sociology is not merely a natural phenomenon, but something with meaning, then time can also be treated experientially as a meaningful phenomenon. In phenomenological sociology, time is not merely a category of cognition of the external observer, but is already considered as another synthetic dimension within the object of observation itself. However, to be more thorough, the fact that time was already present in the object itself had to be considered in the following way. In other words, the selection of what is significant among various aspects of time, self-reflection on such selection, etc., as well as the temporal aspects necessary for such selection and self-reflection, are themselves constructed by the object itself, using its meaning (9)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f1b015a594059e01",
      "text": "The question of time is a question of meaning. Time does not precede meaning, but meaning precedes time. With the shift from phenomenological sociology to sociological phenomenology, the starting point must also be changed in this way. Phenomenological sociology's initial assumption of subjective time forces us to ask the difficult question of how objectivity can be achieved by first discussing the whole/part of the subject's interior, and then reaching the exterior. In contrast, sociological phenomenology does not presuppose systemic time in social systems. As mentioned earlier, communication can only be something of a communication, which means not only that the environment cannot exist without a relationship with the social system, but also that the social system cannot exist without a relationship with the environment. This can be expressed as follows. In other words, a system is a system and its environment."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "92f479ff9d7ca7f5",
      "text": "Phenomenological sociology, by presupposing an unquestionable subject as a grounding system, could develop the discussion from subjective time. However, such naivete is no longer permissible if we are more thorough in our discovery of orientation. To aspire means to differentiate, to draw a distinction (Lu㎞ann1996a:31). Therefore, we cannot assume internal time and from there consider synchronicity with the outside world. On the contrary, time must be meaningfully constituted only in relation to its synchronicity with the environment. If a system can only be in relation to its environment, it cannot be assumed to be identical to it in an ontological sense. Identity is also a phenomenon that becomes possible only through meaning within the system/environment distinction, and is open to a wide variety of possibilities for definition. Therefore, meaning precedes all subjects. Meaning must be a basic concept, not merely something conceived by a subject (Luhmann 1971=, 1987). It is a subjectless concept of meaning. If the social world is to be meaningfully constituted, meaning should have been the basic concept from the very beginning, rather than a problem to be thematized. Perhaps this is the first time that social science can be clearly distinguished from the natural sciences. Socioscience is concerned with all systems that operate using meaning, i.e., both the cognitive system and the social system. In this view, sociology cannot be satisfied with considering only that which is subjective in terms of time. Empirical sociology and anthropology have long pointed out that there is a unique social time that exists in each society between subjective and objective time (10). (10) Theorizing about social time becomes possible only when we consider the question of time as a question of meaning."
