    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1508792fbbaebef5",
      "text": "As mentioned above, this chapter does not start and end with time itself, but rather with the system/environmental synchronicity relation. This relation itself is not yet time, but by not presupposing time, the existential-metaphysical question of what time is in the first place, which goes back to its source, is avoided. The question of time is rather framed as a constructionist one. That is, how is time achieved through a synchronous relationship between system and environment (Luhmann-1990b; Luhmann1996b:309)? However, it is not possible to go into the whole picture of how time is constructed from the simultaneity of the system and the environment in the following sections. As we have already mentioned, we will limit our discussion to the relationship with the second-order observer's observation of the social system, the observer, and ask the following questions. In other words, how can the aspect of \"as it is now\" in system time be as it is now? Observing how and why a system observes something is not the only way to observe its current state as selectively manifested by the system. The \"as-is\" aspect of system time is always a blind spot for the system, since it is the starting point for all observations by the system. Therefore, the second-order observation. Therefore, the second-order observation is to observe how the system can be as it is now. In the first place, the very phrase \"as it is now\" suggests that it is only a choice based on the assumption of other possibilities, which could be either this way or that way. This alone does not leave unanswered the question of how this could be so now. In fact, the core of system formation is not merely the fact that elements occur and processes (whether we call them sustainable or not) are formed, but that they are a choice among various possibilities (Luhmann 1975:22=1986:8). In other words, rather than the system presupposing the elements of the system, the elements of the system must be considered to presuppose the system. It is only through a network of possible relationships within the system that elements selectively acquire the qualities that make them elements of the system (Luhmann1984:41-44=1993/95:31-35), and only now are they manifested as such."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6a7034c02bfdfcd5",
      "text": "Therefore, I would like to discuss how the \"as it is now\" can be the \"as it will be now\" from the perspective of the conclusion. The present state of \"as it is now\" can only exist as it is now when it is defined on a dual plane of past and future, that is, in the context of the entire system time. This is not as obvious as it may seem. It can be said that today's social system theory, which holds that the past and the future are only the level of the present, is rather commonly interpreted as a kind of present-centered theory, as is the case with phenomenology.11 However, the present is not the only level of the past and the future, but it is also the only level of the present. (11) However, when we realize that the factors that emerge in the present are selections among various possibilities based on the system, we are forced to change our understanding of social system theory as being present-centered."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f090a86f5796a773",
      "text": "In order to quickly discuss the above, we would like to point out the following important, but often overlooked, point. This is that not only the creation of elements, but also their disappearance, is based on the system. At first glance, this may appear to be directly contained in the so-called autopoiesis concept of continuous reproduction of elements by the system itself. But to be precise, \"the formal definition of orthopoiesis gives no indication of the span of time in which elements exist\" (Luhma, 1990:8=1996:19). At the biological level, which is the origin of this concept, we can assume with no particular difficulty that mortal decay is inevitable in any organism, and that the consequent constant alternation of cells and intracellular molecules may be considered as a matter of course in itself. But it is not a social system. However, it is not necessarily true that a social system will inevitably decline toward death, as is the case with organisms. Rather, social systems must create their own decline (Luhmann 1990:9=1996:20). Therefore, we cannot assume that elements appear and disappear on their own as a result of continuous i-production. Without the system's enforcement of disappearance, the elements would remain as they are. Although today's social system theory refers to elements as \"events\" that disappear as soon as they appear, this is not such a simple assertion for the reasons I have already mentioned. The eventuality and instantaneousness of an element must be given a theory other than the formal definition of autopoiesis."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5ae0060bb38b2c11",
      "text": "The same is true of the above statement that the core of system formation does not lie in the fact that elements occur and processes are formed. However, certain elements are identified in the process as being different from the former and the latter. Events are the happening that forms the difference between the \"before\" and the \"after\" (Luhmann 1990:10=1996:22). This identification, however, fixes a particular element in place, but it does not create or eliminate the element. It only forms the facticity of the process that takes place over time, but does not express the selectivity of the elements. In fact, unlike what is usually assumed, process and its analogous metaphors such as flow and continuity are actually undifferentiated from the spatial and phenomenal dimensions that underlie motion representations, and have not yet reached a single independent dimension called time (Luhmann 1990b: 97, 98). Luhmann1990b: 97, 98). Therefore, it does not explain the temporality of elements as events, such as appearances and disappearances. At this point, we would like to recall our earlier observation that the question of time is a question of meaning."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1963b523d84e8056",
      "text": "Meaning is an excess of possibilities, and all possibilities other than those that might be manifested as the center of orientation are preserved in the form of horizons. Therefore, the system is always forced to make choices according to its meaning, and it must constantly renew the differences between manifestations and possibilities. This fundamental instability of meaning in the social system is linked to the problem of complexity. This is because meaning reflects exorbitant complexity as a constant constraint on choice (Luhmann1984:92-98=1993/95:92-98). How, then, does the system increase the complexity that cannot be completely controlled, that is, that cannot be completely transparent, in order to achieve a higher degree of progression despite the fact that it has been domesticated, so to speak, as inherent complexity? In this case, the following must be considered. In other words, what is indicated by the increase in system-specific complexity is not merely a quantitative expansion of inter-elemental relationships. Increased system complexity refers to the quantitative expansion of inter-elemental relationships as well as to the increased selectivity of the system structure in response to these relationships (Luhmann 1975:207, 208= 1986:225-226). In other words, as the amount of choices increases, the problem of selection emerges, and therefore the feasibility must be limited structurally at all times. Only when complexity is qualitatively defined and ordered by structure can it be called system complexity and its increase be discussed. System complexity exists only as structured complexity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "37b32eb4575ee902",
      "text": "What is more important as a clue to approaching the problem of system time is not the process before or after, but rather this structure. For only when the quantity, or complexity, of realizable relationships among elements expands, and with it the ability to select structures that define elemental qualities, can the system be freed from the need to react to the environment in a synchronous - versus - versus - reaction, and thus be free to take on a fixed temporality separate from the outside world. The system is free from the need to respond to the environment in a synchronous - versus - - response, and can acquire a unique temporality separate from the outside world. In this respect, the issue of fixed time in a system is first and foremost a complex one. It is this fixed time that gives the elements temporality as an event and allows the system to self-reproduce by constantly generating and deleting elements. In particular, since systems today are considered to be systems that self-reproduce autonomously despite their isolation from the environment and their closed nature, the entirety of their fixed time has a definitive meaning for the eventuality of the elements. The structure of a system is the structure of expectations (Luhmann 1984:139=1993/95:147), and a self-regulating, closed system is not only capable of self-reproduction, but also of creating a structure of expectations for its own sake, rather than externally, but also of creating a new structure of expectations that would violate its own expectations. In order to produce newness that will contradict our expectations, and to provide room for other factors to develop, we must absorb the newness thus generated into the oldness again. To this end, the system makes the entirety of the possibilities of manifesting elements its own invisible horizon in the temporal form of past/future. The system temporalizes its own complexity in terms of the past/future distinction. The system temporalizes its own complexity in terms of past/future, because only then can elements be destabilized. The duality of the horizon is multiplied when we consider the present of the future or the present of the past. Both have their own future and past. The temporalstructure of time is itself the \"future of the future present .... ... This reflexivity alone makes possible the abandonment of something like a stable and lasting presence\" (Luhmann 1990:11=1996:23)a"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b4063751c9aa87b2",
      "text": "Elements are not unstable in themselves. It becomes unstable and eventful in the uncertainty of the double horizon of past and future, and the temporal phase of the present can take on its unique status as a boundary between past and future. The uniqueness of being a boundary is that it belongs to both sides of the distinction, but at the same time it does not belong to either side. The present as a boundary, in other words, is a mixture of the old of the past and the new of the future, yet it is different from both of them. Only in this phase would the creation and disappearance of elements be possible. It is an ambivalent place where events can appear and lose their novelty at the same time. By including the past and the future, the system can produce newness that contradicts the structure of its own expectations in the present, and then absorb that newness into the old again. Therefore, the continuous self-reproduction of the current system is not possible without either the past or the future. [[Verzeitlichung]] refers here to the production of the difference between the past and the future. If only the past exists for the system, i.e., if the present of the manifest action is merely a repetition of the past, the system will not reproduce itself (wieesist) only as it is now. On the other hand, if only the future exists, the system will understand itself as a constant deviation from its own fixed state, for example, as a goal, and will fall into the deviation of deviation upon deviation. A system gains self-organization that allows it to continue to learn only if it is oriented toward the difference between the past and the future and, in this sense, produces time\" (Luhmann 1997:60-61). The elements of a system first acquire their eventuality in the whole of system time, which includes both past and future, and are then temporalized (13). This in turn triggers the various possibilities that may emerge in the system and further increases its complexity. Time is an \"extension of choice\" (Luhmann 1980:239)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cd5365b8f0218379",
      "text": "As a consequence of the above brief considerations, we can say that the present is defined by the past and the future. For the first time in the temporalization of the distinction between the past and the future, the present as such can exist as an unstable and selective thing that can arise or perish. However, this does not deny that self-reproduction of the system can only take place in the present, nor does it imply any kind of determinism. Even if the past and the future define the present, they do so on a level playing field, not as a linear process of causality. However, the concept of time in social system theory cannot be understood only as present-centered. Not only are the past and the future the horizons of the present, but the present also becomes unstable for the first time in the whole of this time, appearing and disappearing as it does now, as a concrete, so to speak, living thing with a limited life span (14). (14) The theoretical ideal of self-reproduction in an autonomous, closed system can be more accurately generalized to social systems by taking this into consideration. As briefly mentioned earlier, the formal definition of so-called autopoiesis itself does not say anything about the time width of elements. Only after the social system is given a theory of system time that further includes past and future, are its elements thoroughly temporalized, becoming events that arise and perish, setting in motion the system's ceaseless self-reproduction."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "42f8e6ab2383b616",
      "text": "Although social systems theory has not clarified this, self-reproduction of a system is inseparable from the issue of system time. This seems to be almost the same as the situation discussed above, where elements of a system can be created and destroyed only in the context of the entire system time, including the past and the future (15). (15) Moreover, the current events produced in the entire system time make possible the past and the future, which are the horizon of the current events, and this continues as the self-reproduction of the system. Thus, system self-reproduction means self-reproduction of system time as it is. In other words, if the system is self-reliant, then time is also self-reliant, in the sense that there is an autonomous and closed cyclic relationship between the present and the past and the future, and the past and the future produce the present. If this is the case, we cannot assume primacy for any of the temporal phases of past, present, and future, including the concept of time that is naively present-centric. From the theoretical standpoint that systems self-reproduce in an autonomous and closed fashion, these temporal phases must also be mutually regulated, more like a network than a hierarchy. In this view, then, there cannot be any fundamental, isochronous non-temporality that precedes the composition of systemic time (16). (16) What constitutes time is not some non-temporal source, but time itself. The stability and sameness of a system are also dynamic only insofar as time continually produces itself, and only after a certain period of identical non-temporality. Its stability is based on instability\" (Luhmann 1990:10=1996:21)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a5a435bb77b12c8f",
      "text": "In place of a conclusion, I would like to close with just one simple suggestion, related to the discussion at the end of the previous chapter, as a basis for developing a sociological phenomenology of systemic time in the future. I have already mentioned that we cannot assume a fundamental and identical non-temporality that precedes the composition of time, but I have already hinted at a different kind of non-temporality in this paper. It is the difference between the system and the environment, and its simultaneity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fb18b6b5d1d00e34",
      "text": "If we maintain a heteronomous approach, the first thing is simply the simultaneity of the system and the environment, not the system time or the source of the system time. Therefore, we should not think of synchronicity as a mutually subjective, mutually shared single moment in time, based on the initial assumption of the time of each subject as itself. Rather, \"synchronicity is the fundamental fact that precedes all temporality\" (Luhmann 1990b:98). Only through difference from a synchronous environment does each system acquire its own specific temporality, or rather, its own specificity within each system time, and not the other way around. Therefore, the question of system time is different from the philosophical conception of consciousness, and is not limited to the mere question of the \"internal\" time of the system in terms of the mutually regulating relationship between the whole and its parts within system time. The mutually regular relationships of past, present, and future discussed above can be self-contained as a temporality unique to the system only when they differ from those of the outside (environment). In other words, because the system \"ages with\" its environment, it preserves its own past and future through the difference between them, and also lives in its own unique way in the present."
    },
