      "type": "edit",
      "id": "e6b5688f8f833c16",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "e6b5688f8f833c16",
        "text": "The main topic of this paper is system time in social systems. In today's theories of social systems, references to time are made quite frequently, as is evident, for example, in the \"thorough temporalization of elementary concepts\" (Luhmann 1984:28=1993/95:16). (1) However, it is not clear why this reference to time is so often necessary. It is generally accepted that social system theory is heavily influenced by phenomenology. In the same way that phenomenology regarded the problem domain of time as the most fundamental,(2) the problem of time may also fundamentally support the entire system theory. For the record, such speculations are not merely groundless to open a debate, nor are they intended to justify the system theory by borrowing the authority of an establi-cation called phenomenology, which has a wide following. In fact, today's social system theory has a more fundamental internal relationship to phenomenology than merely an influence relationship. For some reason, the following points are often overlooked. In other words, communication, which is an element of the social system, can only be about something at all times. This corresponds to the structure of directionality that makes phenomenology possible. In other words, something communicated is always an internal manifestation of the social system, or in other words, a social phenomenon, as opposed to an awareness phenomenon. The reason why social systems theory must address the issue of system time is that this social phenomenon is related to the current state of the system at any given time. A given social phenomenon"
      },
      "date": 1710933377495
