    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "e6b5688f8f833c16",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "e6b5688f8f833c16",
        "text": "The main topic of this paper is system time in social systems. In today's theories of social systems, references to time are made quite frequently, as is evident, for example, in the \"thorough temporalization of elementary concepts\" (Luhmann 1984:28=1993/95:16). (1) However, it is not clear why this reference to time is so often necessary. It is generally accepted that social system theory is heavily influenced by phenomenology. In the same way that phenomenology regarded the problem domain of time as the most fundamental,(2) the problem of time may also fundamentally support the entire system theory. For the record, such speculations are not merely groundless to open a debate, nor are they intended to justify the system theory by borrowing the authority of an establi-cation called phenomenology, which has a wide following. In fact, today's social system theory has a more fundamental internal relationship to phenomenology than merely an influence relationship. For some reason, the following points are often overlooked. In other words, communication, which is an element of the social system, can only be about something at all times. This corresponds to the structure of directionality that makes phenomenology possible. In other words, something communicated is always an internal manifestation of the social system, or in other words, a social phenomenon, as opposed to an awareness phenomenon. The reason why social systems theory must address the issue of system time is that this social phenomenon is related to the current state of the system at any given time."
      },
      "date": 1710933492400
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "cf6497072f1b647c",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "cf6497072f1b647c",
        "text": "The fact that a social phenomenon appears as it does now, and changes as it does, is synonymous with the constant changes of system time. However, it is not easy, but rather rather difficult, to discuss time in social systems, given the current level of sociological theory. First of all, the existence of the social system itself may be questioned to a greater or lesser degree. In this respect, in the genealogy of the philosophy of consciousness, the certainty of the thinking self was the starting point, so it was not so difficult to discuss the time of consciousness as a consequence of the development from this point. In contrast, however, in the case of social systems, the very existence of the system itself is in doubt for theories of action that do not recognize irreducible emergent properties and for a kind of utilitarianism that regards the system concept as a mere model for analysis, and unless this part is confirmed, there is little room to discuss systemic time. Therefore, we cannot discuss system time unless we are sure of this part. Therefore, before a naive discussion of social system time as a subject can be made, its thematic potential must first be questioned. As an aside, without any further argument, let me suggest that the question of the existence of a social system is almost synonymous with the question of system time. In other words, it would not be right to say that the social system exists first as a kind of pure ego, and then we can finally discuss system time in analogy with the experiential flow. If we assume the order to be all the way through, it seems more plausible that the opposite is true, i.e., that we can discuss system time and then thematize the reality of the system. This is because the autonomy of a system can be described as \"temporal autonomy\" (Bergmann 1981:110). A system processes external events according to its internal temporal order, and therefore must always understand its boundary as a \"temporal boundary\" (Bergmann 1981:109). System-specific time is what guarantees (or even enforces) the system's differentiation from its environment and its autonomy (3). Therefore, in other words, a system without inherent time cannot reproduce itself autonomously and cannot be realistic. This paper, however, does not address this issue head-on. It would require more space. Therefore, keeping these issues in mind, we will only ask how the \"as it is now (JetztundSo)\" aspect of system time can exist in the first place as an issue for the time being(4). As is well known, the challenge of modern social system theory is to observe how and why the system is being observed. This differs from a theory that attempts an objectivistic mercantilist viewpoint, such as that of a patient with a theoretical disease, in that it sets the problem in the first place. The difference between the two may be characterized as a shift from existence theory to recognition theory in system theory. Social system theory views various social systems not as mono, which is an internal relationship between the whole and its parts, but as one of the world's subjects with its own external environment.5 As an illustration of this, the theory of social systems is a theory that considers the social system as an entity with its own external environment, and as such, it is a theory of social systems. (5) As an illustration, social system theory is a second-order observer that observes the observer called the social system. And this is precisely the reason for setting the subject of this paper as mentioned above. In other words, the \"as-is\" aspect of system time is the starting point for observation of the system as it exists at any given time, and is always a blind spot or, in the manner of phenomenology, always anonymous to the system itself. Therefore, the observation of how such and such an aspect could be as it is now is considered to be a central issue for the social system theory of the second-order observer. Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
      },
      "after": "e6b5688f8f833c16",
      "date": 1710933493463
