    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "0ed17c36f7086c69",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0ed17c36f7086c69",
        "text": "Therefore, before a naive discussion of social system time as a subject can be made, its thematic potential must first be questioned. As an aside, without any further argument, let me suggest that the question of the existence of a social system is almost synonymous with the question of system time. In other words, it would not be right to say that the social system exists first as a kind of pure ego, and then we can finally discuss system time in analogy with the experiential flow. If we assume the order to be all the way through, it seems more plausible that the opposite is true, i.e., that we can discuss system time and then thematize the reality of the system. This is because the autonomy of a system can be described as \"temporal autonomy\" (Bergmann 1981:110). A system processes external events according to its internal temporal order, and therefore must always understand its boundary as a \"temporal boundary\" (Bergmann 1981:109). System-specific time is what guarantees (or even enforces) the system's differentiation from its environment and its autonomy (3). Therefore, in other words, a system without inherent time cannot reproduce itself autonomously and cannot be realistic. This paper, however, does not address this issue head-on. It would require more space. Therefore, keeping these issues in mind, we will only ask how the \"as it is now (JetztundSo)\" aspect of system time can exist in the first place as an issue for the time being(4). As is well known, the challenge of modern social system theory is to observe how and why the system is being observed. This differs from a theory that attempts an objectivistic mercantilist viewpoint, such as that of a patient with a theoretical disease, in that it sets the problem in the first place. The difference between the two may be characterized as a shift from existence theory to recognition theory in system theory. Social system theory views various social systems not as mono, which is an internal relationship between the whole and its parts, but as one of the world's subjects with its own external environment.5 As an illustration of this, the theory of social systems is a theory that considers the social system as an entity with its own external environment, and as such, it is a theory of social systems. (5) As an illustration, social system theory is a second-order observer that observes the observer called the social system. And this is precisely the reason for setting the subject of this paper as mentioned above. In other words, the \"as-is\" aspect of system time is the starting point for observation of the system as it exists at any given time, and is always a blind spot or, in the manner of phenomenology, always anonymous to the system itself. Therefore, the observation of how such and such an aspect could be as it is now is considered to be a central issue for the social system theory of the second-order observer."
      },
      "after": "cf6497072f1b647c",
      "date": 1710933572896
