    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "20b80d25a4ac4266",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "20b80d25a4ac4266",
        "text": "Therefore, in other words, a system without inherent time cannot reproduce itself autonomously and cannot be realistic. This paper, however, does not address this issue head-on. It would require more space. Therefore, keeping these issues in mind, we will only ask how the \"as it is now (JetztundSo)\" aspect of system time can exist in the first place as an issue for the time being(4). As is well known, the challenge of modern social system theory is to observe how and why the system is being observed. This differs from a theory that attempts an objectivistic mercantilist viewpoint, such as that of a patient with a theoretical disease, in that it sets the problem in the first place. The difference between the two may be characterized as a shift from existence theory to recognition theory in system theory. Social system theory views various social systems not as mono, which is an internal relationship between the whole and its parts, but as one of the world's subjects with its own external environment.5 As an illustration of this, the theory of social systems is a theory that considers the social system as an entity with its own external environment, and as such, it is a theory of social systems. (5) As an illustration, social system theory is a second-order observer that observes the observer called the social system. And this is precisely the reason for setting the subject of this paper as mentioned above. In other words, the \"as-is\" aspect of system time is the starting point for observation of the system as it exists at any given time, and is always a blind spot or, in the manner of phenomenology, always anonymous to the system itself. Therefore, the observation of how such and such an aspect could be as it is now is considered to be a central issue for the social system theory of the second-order observer."
      },
