      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "803a4f632d512851",
        "text": "According to phenomenological sociology, social science contains issues that have different meanings from those of the natural sciences. To thematize these issues, it was thought necessary to support the analysis of internal temporal consciousness of phenomenology. In reality, however, phenomenological sociology seems to have overturned rather than assisted the phenomenological view, as later summarized by the term \"epoché of natural attitudes. Originally, in Husserl's phenomenology, a natural attitude was an attitude that made naturalized and spatialized notions of time self-evident, and this attitude had to be returned in order to approach an inner sense of time.7 However, in contrast to this, Husserl's phenomenology is not a natural attitude, but an attitude that is not naturalized, but an attitude that is not naturalized, but an attitude that is not naturalized, but an attitude that is not naturalized, and this attitude has to be returned in order to approach an inner sense of time. In contrast, phenomenological sociology considered that the natural attitude is an immersion in continuity, and that this naivete must be returned for rational action, and that an intermediate goal must be established in a reflective way. This view may lead to the following conclusion. The meaning of an act, in other words, is distinguished by the spatialization of subjective time. Internal time must be spatialized as divisible through reflection. Only then can the meaning of experience be made salient, and the meaning of action, i.e., the rational relation between purpose and means, be made possible. Therefore, according to phenomenological sociology, the unit of action is a function of the \"span\" of the projection (Schutz 1932:62=1982:83)(8). In the end, however, phenomenological sociology does not distinguish between the main"
