      "type": "edit",
      "id": "1508792fbbaebef5",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "1508792fbbaebef5",
        "text": "As mentioned above, this chapter does not start and end with time itself, but rather with the system/environmental synchronicity relation. This relation itself is not yet time, but by not presupposing time, the existential-metaphysical question of what time is in the first place, which goes back to its source, is avoided. The question of time is rather framed as a constructionist one. That is, how is time achieved through a synchronous relationship between system and environment (Luhmann-1990b; Luhmann1996b:309)? However, it is not possible to go into the whole picture of how time is constructed from the simultaneity of the system and the environment in the following sections. As we have already mentioned, we will limit our discussion to the relationship with the second-order observer's observation of the social system, the observer, and ask the following questions. In other words, how can the aspect of \"as it is now\" in system time be as it is now? Observing how and why a system observes something is not the only way to observe its current state as selectively manifested by the system. The \"as-is\" aspect of system time is always a blind spot for the system, since it is the starting point for all observations by the system. Therefore, the second-order observation. Therefore, the second-order observation is to observe how the system can be as it is now. In the first place, the very phrase \"as it is now\" suggests that it is only a choice based on the assumption of other possibilities, which could be either this way or that way. This alone does not leave unanswered the question of how this could be so now. In fact, the core of system formation is not merely the fact that elements occur and processes (whether we call them sustainable or not) are formed, but that they are a choice among various possibilities (Luhmann 1975:22=1986:8). In other words, rather than the system presupposing the elements of the system, the elements of the system must be considered to presuppose the system. It is only through a network of possible relationships within the system that elements selectively acquire the qualities that make them elements of the system (Luhmann1984:41-44=1993/95:31-35), and only now are they manifested as such."
      },
      "date": 1710935233771
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "6a7034c02bfdfcd5",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "6a7034c02bfdfcd5",
        "text": "Therefore, I would like to discuss how the \"as it is now\" can be the \"as it will be now\" from the perspective of the conclusion. The present state of \"as it is now\" can only exist as it is now when it is defined on a dual plane of past and future, that is, in the context of the entire system time. This is not as obvious as it may seem. It can be said that today's social system theory, which holds that the past and the future are only the level of the present, is rather commonly interpreted as a kind of present-centered theory, as is the case with phenomenology.11 However, the present is not the only level of the past and the future, but it is also the only level of the present. (11) However, when we realize that the factors that emerge in the present are selections among various possibilities based on the system, we are forced to change our understanding of social system theory as being present-centered."
