    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "42f8e6ab2383b616",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "42f8e6ab2383b616",
        "text": "Although social systems theory has not clarified this, self-reproduction of a system is inseparable from the issue of system time. This seems to be almost the same as the situation discussed above, where elements of a system can be created and destroyed only in the context of the entire system time, including the past and the future (15). (15) Moreover, the current events produced in the entire system time make possible the past and the future, which are the horizon of the current events, and this continues as the self-reproduction of the system. Thus, system self-reproduction means self-reproduction of system time as it is. In other words, if the system is self-reliant, then time is also self-reliant, in the sense that there is an autonomous and closed cyclic relationship between the present and the past and the future, and the past and the future produce the present. If this is the case, we cannot assume primacy for any of the temporal phases of past, present, and future, including the concept of time that is naively present-centric. From the theoretical standpoint that systems self-reproduce in an autonomous and closed fashion, these temporal phases must also be mutually regulated, more like a network than a hierarchy. In this view, then, there cannot be any fundamental, isochronous non-temporality that precedes the composition of systemic time (16). (16) What constitutes time is not some non-temporal source, but time itself. The stability and sameness of a system are also dynamic only insofar as time continually produces itself, and only after a certain period of identical non-temporality. Its stability is based on instability\" (Luhmann 1990:10=1996:21)."
      },
      "after": "cd5365b8f0218379",
