    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "fb18b6b5d1d00e34",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "fb18b6b5d1d00e34",
        "text": "If we maintain a heteronomous approach, the first thing is simply the simultaneity of the system and the environment, not the system time or the source of the system time. Therefore, we should not think of synchronicity as a mutually subjective, mutually shared single moment in time, based on the initial assumption of the time of each subject as itself. Rather, \"synchronicity is the fundamental fact that precedes all temporality\" (Luhmann 1990b:98). Only through difference from a synchronous environment does each system acquire its own specific temporality, or rather, its own specificity within each system time, and not the other way around. Therefore, the question of system time is different from the philosophical conception of consciousness, and is not limited to the mere question of the \"internal\" time of the system in terms of the mutually regulating relationship between the whole and its parts within system time. The mutually regular relationships of past, present, and future discussed above can be self-contained as a temporality unique to the system only when they differ from those of the outside (environment). In other words, because the system \"ages with\" its environment, it preserves its own past and future through the difference between them, and also lives in its own unique way in the present."
